text: Well.  I'm a little excited, and a lot irked at the same time. Flatliners is very dear ot my heart. Seeing it as a teen was an experience, back in the day. But what made it work, among other things, was its simplicity, its lack of flashy visual prowess. I fear that the "creaturesque" look of the apparitions will take away from the original's more natural dread. Where Flatliners OG succeeded in creating a genuine sense of being stalked, of otherworldly proximity, this one seems to go instead in the way of cheap jumpscares and rehashed techniques.  I am, therefore, sad.  (I'll still watch it, if only for the faint hope that it's actually good.)
author: Le Zblugg

text: First of all, don't remake every move from the late 20th century that had any kind of cult following. text: YES OK WE GET IT IT IS NOT AN ORIGINAL FILM. OH. MY. GOD. Yes, Hollywood has run out of ideas, but so, seemingly, has the youtube comment section ffs. Maybe put more than one braincell to work and make an original comment about why you actually think the trailer makes this movie look bad. Personally, my interest is piqued because this has a lot of actors I like; Ellen Page (she alone would be enough of a selling point, honestly), Kiersey Clemons and Diego Luna (imdb also lists Kiefer Sutherland, which might make for an interesting tie-in with the original). The score sounds pretty original and creepily atmospheric, and the CG doesn't look half bad. So for me, even though I am as tired as everyone else of the reboots/remakes/sequels/etc and wish for more original content, the trailer looks interesting enough that I'll probably go see it.

text: While true to its source material, along with well acting and fine directing, the fun and intriguing concept in "Flatliners" gets squandered very early on, as we're subjected to another dead on arrival franchise attempt by SONY. Only ONE actor from the original ‚ÄúFlatliners‚Äù movie makes a return here and yet, the film isn‚Äôt considered a sequel......which I don‚Äôt have a problem with. The problems that I DO have with this movie is WAY too many to count. How about trying to explain just how utterly incompetent and useless most of the central characters in this movie are (Ellen Page being the ONLY exception), especially when they freakin‚Äô John Travolta from ‚ÄúPhenomenon‚Äù themselves? Not only is it unneeded, but there‚Äôs no attempt at fleshing out what or WHO they really are, giving you very little reason to like, care or even connect with these characters. Even before we get UP to THAT point, the entire arc behind this movie makes very little sense, since this movie is LACKING something that it actually REQUIRES to ACTUALLY be somewhat decent. It gets relatively confusing by the third act of the film, it fails TREMENDOUSLY at being a horror film, the dialogue is terrible and PLEASE don‚Äôt get me started on the screenplay. The film is almost completely self-aware of how bad it is and it‚Äôs filled with so many unintentional moments that it almost comes out being unintentional funny......  .....except it‚Äôs NOT.   Almost EVERYTHING about this flick is awful because a premise like this HAD been done well before in the past. It had the potential to work once again and yet it still didn‚Äôt work out the way it was supposed to.  Overall, "Flatliners" foolishly tries to breath new life into a film that should've been left alone......but its completely unaware that it had already lost its pulse.

text: Let us be honest. If they could actually prove anything through a method like this, then people would have something to be fearful of. Normally everyone thinks and agrees that when you die that is it. Nothing else. But if it was possible to even reveal that there was more, even in the smallest form, no hallucination, no tricks, absolute concrete evidence, then the general consensus that was agreed upon would be threatened with questions leading experts DON'T want answered or established facts proven to be wrong. Everyone who was residing within the safety of an ambiguous answer, or a lack of one, would suddenly find themselves in an uncomfortable position of wanting to ask "Is there more? Which religion, if any of them, at all, had their bases covered?".  You see, the upside to this movie is that this concept has been done for stories repeatedly. What happens when you die, and if there is an afterlife, and whether the answers would weigh over your heads and dictate how you live your life. Bah, but that was all just entertainment, it cannot affect YOU the audience, because it is not happening to you! That only happens in crappy movies!! (But seriously, I would totally find it awesome to be living in the universe of the MCU, and NOT Transformers)
